I'll provide you with a simple example of an HTTP client using Rust's `hyper` library. This example shows how to perform an HTTP GET request and display the response body as a string.

First, you'll need Cargo.toml dependencies:

```toml
[dependencies]
hyper = { version = "0.14", features = ["full"] }
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }
```

And here's a simple example of an HTTP client:

```rust
use hyper::{Body, Client, Uri};
use hyper::client::HttpConnector;
use std::error::Error;
use tokio::runtime::Runtime;

async fn simple_get_request(uri: &str) -> Result<String, Box<dyn Error + Send + Sync>> {
    // Create the HTTP client
    let client = Client::new();

    // Parse the URL
    let uri: Uri = uri.parse()?;

    // Send the HTTP GET request and wait for the response
    let mut resp = client.get(uri).await?;

    // Read the response fully
    let body_bytes = hyper::body::to_bytes(resp.body_mut()).await?;

    // Convert bytes to a string
    let body_str = String::from_utf8(body_bytes.to_vec())?;

    // Return the response body
    Ok(body_str)
}

fn main() {
    // Create a tokio runtime to execute the request
    let rt = Runtime::new().unwrap();

    // URL to fetch
    let url = "http://example.com/";

    // Block and wait for the request to complete
    let body = rt.block_on(simple_get_request(url)).unwrap();

    // Print the response body
    println!("Response body: {}", body);
}
```

In this example, we have created an async function `simple_get_request` that takes a URL as an input and returns the response body as a string. The main function creates a tokio runtime to execute the async function, fetches the desired URL, and prints the response body.
